DURBAN - Residents of a low-cost housing complex in in Howell Road, Sydenham barricaded the entrance of the complex on Tuesday with burning tyres and rubble to prevent the Red Ants from evicting them. At least 150 tenants at the housing complex were served with eviction letters last week following a long-standing battle with  First Metro Housing, a non-profit organisation that is involved in the development and management of social housing on behalf of the eThekwini Municipality. For years, tenants have claimed they were promised ownership of their units after a certain time. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. The complex was built in 2001 for those with incomes of up to R3 500 a month. On Tuesday, residents formed human chain outside the housing complex and vowed to fight any attempts to evict them. This after word spread that they were to be evicted, early on Tuesday.
"We need to fight, things are bad. We need to fight,"  a resident said as Red Ants - private company hired to carried out evictions - moved in. They had given residents only an hour to move their belongings. To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. Resident Thandi Nyide said she is upset about the impending evictions, after she had lived there since 2012.  She now lives there with her three children who are in school while they deal with the evictions. If evicted they had nowhere to go. Daily News